         <div type="apparatus">
            <p>There are no significant differences between the modern copies. In line 8, for <foreign xml:lang="grc">ξυνὸν</foreign>, <title level="m">AP</title> has <foreign xml:lang="grc">κοῖλον</foreign>. The Byzantine copyist perhaps chose to 'improve' the text, and wrote <foreign xml:lang="grc">κοινὸν</foreign> which was subsequently corrupted to <foreign xml:lang="grc">κοῖλον</foreign> (as editors since Boeckh have conjectured); but see commentary, <ref type="eAla-text" n="V.8" target=".xml"/>.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <ab>The light of virtue shines even for dead men, who, undertaking many labours for their country, established general benefits. The saying fits Asklepiodotos, for whom this city has dedicated this statue as for a founder.</ab>
            <ab>Long time wears away even stone; but the fame of Asklepiodotos' virtues is immortal, the number and kind of privileges which he obtained for his country. In addition to all these, let this adjacent structure of the vaulted chamber be counted as well.</ab>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>For Asklepiodotos see also <ref type="inscription" n="54" target="110069.xml"/>; see discussion at <ref type="eAla-text" n="V.8" target=".xml"/> following.</p>
         </div>
